{{Infobox political party |country = Lithuania |name = Democratic Jewish Union |native_name = Žydų demoktratinish susivienijimas }} The '''Democratic Jewish Union''' ({{lang-lt|Žydų demoktratinish susivienijimas}}, ZDS) was a political coalition in inter-war [[Lithuania]].
==History== The ZDS contested the [[Lithuanian parliamentary election, 1920|Constituent Assembly elections]] in Lithuania in 1920, receiving 6.6% of the vote and winning six seats.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip Stöver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1218 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> The six elected members were [[Simon Yakovlevich Rosenbaum|Rosenbaum]] (Zionist), Soloveitzik (Zionist), Dr. N. Rachmilewitz (Achdut-[[Agudat Israel]]), R. Abraham Popelas (Achdut-Agudat Israel), [[Naphtali Friedman|Nachman Fridman]] ([[Folkspartei]]) and Ozer Finkelstein (Folkspartei). After Fridman's death he was replaced in the assembly by Samuel Landau.<ref name="Greenbaum1995">{{cite book|author=Masha Greenbaum|title=The Jews of Lithuania: a history of a remarkable community, 1316-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E2_ag8xGWMQC&pg=PA216|date=1 January 1995|publisher=Gefen Publishing House Ltd|isbn=978-965-229-132-5|page=216}}</ref>
The party did not contest the [[Lithuanian parliamentary election, 1922|1922]] or [[Lithuanian parliamentary election, 1923|1923 elections]], but returned in [[Lithuanian parliamentary election, 1926|1926]], when it won three seats. However, a military coup saw the [[Seimas]] dissolved in December 1926 and no further multi-party elections were held again until the 1990s.
