{{Muisca sidebar}} [[File:Goranchacha El hijo del Sol.jpg|thumb|right|205px|'''Goranchacha''', one of the mythical creatures in the mythology of the Muisca]] [[File:Muisca raft BOG 04 2012 Museo de Oro 1251.jpg|thumb|right|205px|The [[Muisca raft]], discovered in the 1920s, almost 400 years after the Spanish conquistadores were looking for the basis of the '''''El Dorado''''' legend]] This article describes the '''Muisca mythology'''; the [[mythology]] of the [[Muisca people|Muisca]]. Mythology is different from religion in the sense that myths are usually the combination of real events and/or people with a legendary twist, while religion is purely transcedental. The [[religion]] of the Muisca is described in [[Muisca religion]]; their deities, rituals and sacred sites.
Main contributors to the knowledge of the mythology of the Muisca have been [[List of Muisca scholars|Muisca scholars]] [[Javier Ocampo López]], [[Pedro Simón]], [[Lucas Fernández de Piedrahita]], [[Juan de Castellanos]] and [[conquistador]] [[Gonzalo Jiménez de Quesada]] who was the European making first contact with the Muisca in the 1530s.
== Muisca mythology == The times before the [[Spanish conquest of the Muisca|Spanish conquest]] of the [[Muisca Confederation]] are filled with mythology. The first confirmed human [[Muisca rulers|rulers]] of the two capitals [[Tunja|Hunza]] and [[Bogotá|Bacatá]] are said to have descended from mythical creatures. Apart from that other Muisca myths exist, such as the legendary ''[[El Dorado]]'' and the [[Monster of Lake Tota]].
=== Mythological creatures === Several mythological creatures have been described by the [[chronicler]]s: * [[Thomagata]], said to have been one of the most religious of the ''zaques'', after Idacansás<ref>Ocampo López, 2013, Ch.14, p.85</ref> * [[Idacansás]], allegedly a mythical priest from [[Sogamoso|Sugamuxi]] who was able to change the order of things<ref>Ocampo López, 2013, Ch.12, p.77</ref> * [[Goranchacha]], a mythical ''cacique'' who moved the capital of the northern Muisca from [[Ramiriquí]] to the later capital Hunza<ref>Ocampo López, 2013, Ch.13, p.80</ref> * [[Pacanchique]], according to Muisca myths recovered his fiancé Azay from ruler [[Quemuenchatocha]] by first turning her into a dead person and then bringing her back to life using different plants. He also showed the [[Spanish conquest of the Muisca|Spanish]] conquistadores the way to Nemequene's palace<ref>Ocampo López, 2013, Ch.19, p.104</ref>Other Muisca people where human and mythological character converge are:
* [[Hunzahúa]], first ''[[zaque]]'' of Hunza, allegedly committing [[incest]] with his sister and said to have fled<ref>Ocampo López, 2013, Ch.11, p.70</ref> * [[Meicuchuca]], first ''[[zipa]]'' of Bacatá, one of his wives mythologically turned into a snake<ref>{{es}} [http://pueblosoriginarios.com/sur/caribe/muisca/serpiente.html Meicuchuca, the lover of the snake] - Pueblos Originarios - accessed 05-05-2016</ref>
=== Other Muisca myths === * ''[[El Dorado]]'', the man or city made of gold, that was not so mythical but a main motive for the Spanish to conquer Colombia. The ritual is represented in the [[Muisca raft]], a piece of gold working found in [[Pasca, Cundinamarca|Pasca]] almost 400 years after the arrival of the Spanish * [[Monster of Lake Tota]], allegedly a monstrous snake or fish living in [[Lake Tota]]<ref name="Triana, 1880">{{es}} [https://docs.google.com/open?id=0B-Kqfvt5uQFIMEszNG9ScG5IVFU ''Mitos y Leyendas de Colombia'', Eugenia Villa Posse; Ed. IADAP, 1993; S. 204] - accessed 05-05-2016</ref> * [[Hunzahúa Well]], a well that according to the mythology of the Muisca originated from spilled [[Chicha#Colombia|chicha]] when the mother of [[Hunzahúa]] caught him and his sister Noncetá while they were committing [[incest]]<ref name=PueblosPozo>{{es}} [http://pueblosoriginarios.com/sur/caribe/muisca/pozo.html Hunzahúa Well] - Pueblos Originarios</ref> {{clearboth}}
